the inauspicious image ho center for buddhist studies at stanford skip to main content area home home about the center events people academics research resources partners related links search this site ho center for buddhist studies at stanford the inauspicious image date fri nov 14 2008 4 15pm location encina hall west room 208 program series program series buddhist art lectures 2008 09 speaker s name affiliation sonya rhie quintanilla curator of asian art san diego museum of art the proliferation of images of the buddha and buddhist monks did not occur in indian art until about seven hundred years after the time of the buddha this lecture explores the reasons behind the slow emergence of clerical imagery and the early struggles the buddhist community had in formulating an appropriate icon as a focus for worship speaker's bio speaker s bio sonya rhie quintanilla received a phd in south asian art history from harvard prior to joining sdma she taught south asian art history at uc irvine and as a visiting professor at ucla she has lectured widely and published on many aspects of early indian art her recently published book history of early stone sculpture at mathura ca 150 bce 100 ce provides the first comprehensive chronology of the earliest known stone sculptures from the north indian city of mathura stanford university international comparative & area studies department of religious studies ho center for buddhist studies at stanford stanford university all rights reserved stanford ca 94305 site development by wired moon
